           A few points about assembler programming on the ST
           ==================================================

LEARNING 68000 ASSEMBLER ?
--------------------------
	In addition to the assembler manual, you will need a good 68000
assembler reference book e.g:-

 SYBEX        Programming the 68000               by Steve Williams
 McGRAW-HILL  68000 assembly language programming by Kane, Hawkins & Leventhal.

GOT BUG PROBLEMS ?
------------------
	If you've not programmed a 68000 before be careful with your '.B' '.W'
and '.L' instruction suffixes. Many bugs are caused by missing out a '.L'.
If not specified, most instructions default to the .W (16 bit) mode.

	Note that the Atari ST hardware locations and the first 2k of ram
( $0000 to $07ff ) are accessible in 68000 supervisor mode only. Most of
your programs should be running in user mode so you will have to call TOS
to switch into supervisor mode to access hardware like the colour palette
or 68000 vectors or system variables. If you inadvertently access these
protected addresses in user mode you may crash the system - mushroom clouds or
bombs may appear on the screen or the computer may just hang. Be particularly
careful in programs not to put typos in your addresses - this can cause
the 68000 to access a priviledged location and crash (e.g. missing out #'s
from immediate mode instructions often causes an access to protected ram below
$800) and yet can be very difficult to spot when looking over a listing.

	Most of the Hardware is best accessed via the operating system trap
calls. This method does not require you to set supervisor mode and is an awful
lot less likely to cause problems. In particular, do not try to access the sound
chip registers directly via their i/o addresses unless you first turn off all
the system interrupts! Unfortunately, fully documenting the numerous operating-
system calls or the GEM calls is beyond the scope of this document or the
assembler manual. Full documentation may be purchased from Atari themselves and
is likely to shortly become available from a number of independent publishing
houses in the form of a flood of 'ST programming guide' type books.

	The line-A graphics interface in TOS version 0.13 contains bugs which
prevent the Assembler SPRITE.ASM demo from functioning correctly (not to
mention quite a few other bugs). If you are using this version of TOS we would
recommend you to obtain a more recent release such as the TOS roms a.s.a.p.

PROBLEMS USING GEM FROM ASSEMBLER ?
-----------------------------------
	Contrary to popular belief, you can do some pretty fancy graphics on
the Atari ST without having to resort to using GEM. The line-A interface is
simpler and faster. GEM really comes into it's own in applications programming,
handling windows, menu's and draw multi-pattern filled elliptical 3D pie charts.
If you want to make extensive use of GEM for graphics it's much easier in C.
	To make full use of GEM you will probably need full documentation
e.g. the official Atari developers' notes. ST programmers guides are at last 
becoming available.


SOME GEMDOS CALLS
=================

	Writing useful programs on the ST is likely to require some knowledge
of operating system calls. This until this information becomes widely available
here are a few guidelines...

a) Get a character from keyboard :-  'cconin'

	move.w	#1,-(sp)	;push code for cconin function
	trap	#1		;will return with key in d0 low word
	addq.l	#2,sp		;restore the stack pointer as it was
* key ascii code now in d0 low word
* scan code is in d0 high word (use SWAP if you want the scancode)


b) Put a character to screen :-  'cconout'

	move.w	#char,-(sp)	;push character to send onto stack
	move.w	#2,-(sp)	;and push code for cconout function
	trap	#1		;call GEMDOS, returns when char sent
	addq.l	#4,sp		;pull what we pushed back off stack


c) Write a string to screen :-  'cconws'

	pea	string		;push address of null terminated string
	move.w	#9,-(sp)	;push code for cconws function
	trap	#1		;call GEMDOS to write the string
	addq.l	#6,sp		;restore the stack as it was

d) Terminating your program :-  'pterm0'

	Unless your assembler program continues indefinitely (like the SPRITE
example) you will no doubt wish to pass control back to the desktop at some
time. This can be done cleanly and easily using the GEMDOS 'terminate process'
call ( proper name is 'pterm0' ). The instruction sequence is :-

	clr.w	-(sp)		;push zero onto stack (code for pterm0)
	trap	#1		;call GEMDOS (will not return)

Other operating system calls have been documented by recent editions of the
American Atari users' magazine 'Antic' , a publication which I would recommend
to anyone who does not have access to the Atari developers information.




	  C programming using the Lattice C compiler on the ST
	  ====================================================

	The Lattice compiler is largely compatible with listings you may see in
magazines for the DR (Alcyon) C compiler. There are however a few minor points
worth noticing:-

1) Default integer size for Lattice is 32 BITS unlike the DR compiler which
   has 16 bit default integers. For this reason programmers usually use defined
   standard portabilty types where this size is important. These types are
   usually contained in an include file called PORTAB.H. Notice that GEM makes
   extensive use of 16 bit integers. Use the short or WORD types instead. See
   example C programs on this disk for examples.

2) Include files at the start of programs may vary. You can generally figure
   out what equivalent include files are necessary from what the program is
   doing. The DR compiler has several header files for use with GEM but the
   Lattice compiler has one (GEMLIB.H) which is generally equivalent to these.

	stdio.h		use this header in programs which use file i/o, that
			includes simple keyboard & screen i/o.
	fcntl.h 	file control header. Generally needed where you need
			more elaborate use of the level 2 i/o functions.
			Contains file access modes etc.
	portab.h	contains a few of the more common portability macros.
			feel free to add to this file as necessary.
	osbind.h	direct equivalent to the DR compiler header file of
			the same name - it contains all of the gemdos, bios
			and xbios macros which allow you to refer to individual
			gemdos/bios/xbios functions by name even though there
			are only 3 real functions.
	math.h		contains external definitions for all of the maths
			functions. (If not declared as double the compiler will
			assume all the math functions to be of type int).
			You should include this file if you wish to use the
			floating point math library functions.
	gemlib.h	contains countless definitions to simplify GEM programs 
			and make them more readable. Include in programs
			which make use of the GEM libray functions.

   In order to familiarise yourself with the compiler it is a good idea to read
   or even take listings of the various header files (all .H files) and the
   linker control files (all ending in .LNK) on the Lattice-C disks. You should
   then have no problems deciding which files you need to include for your
   application.

3) Note that as the OSLIB.H operating system functions are defined as macros
   it is important that they are typed in exactly as in this file i.e. the
   first letter of the function name must be in upper case, rest in lower case
   and there must be no space between the funtion name and the '('.

4) DEVICE I/O: A lot of people are having problems using ST peripherals from
   their C programs. The most direct way to communicate with ST devices (and
   the only way to talk to midi) is to use the assorted gemdos, bios, or xbios
   library functions (listed in OSLIB.H). You will however probably need some
   extra documentation on these functions to make full use of them. Sorry, but
   it wasn't practical to document all of the ST's O.S. functions in the manual
   for the C compiler.
   DEVICE FILENAMES are filenames used to refer to peripheral devices. Version
   0.13 of TOS did not support any device filenames directly although more
   recent versions  (e.g. 0.19 - available in ROM) support the following
   device names:-

	CON:	refers to the 'console' (default standard i/o device)
	AUX:	the serial (RS-232) port.
	PRN:	the parallel printer port.

   File operations with these filenames will instead transfer data to and from
   the appropriate hardware device as a stream file. These are the Atari
   standard device filenames supported by TOS directly and can be used from all
   implementations of assembler, C, Pascal, command line emulators etc.
   PLEASE note that these filenames will not work with version 0.13 of TOS (the
   most common RAM version of TOS.)

4a) AN UNDOCUMENTED FEATURE OF MCC LATTICE-C AND PASCAL.

	The Metacomco C and Pascal runtime systems have their own internal
   device filenames which can be used for command line re-direction of standard
   i/o and also as device filenames from within the program:-

	CON:	the console device.
	AXI:	serial RS-232 for input.
	AXO:	serial RS-232 for output.
	LST:	the parallel printer port.
	NIL:	a null device. Throws away anything sent to it.

   These filenames will also work with version 0.13 of TOS. The standard Atari
   names are generally preferable to the MCC runtime system ones since they are
   portable to other ST language implementations and are more direct.

5) ENCLOSED FREEBIE - LINE-A GRAPHICS LIBRARIES.
	Assembler programmers have easy access to the Line-A graphics interface
   at the heart of GEM-vdi for faster, simpler, and more compact and efficient
   use of the ST's graphics. With these enclosed Line-A module linked in you
   can use the Line-A from C for fast point-plotting, line-drawing, & sprites!
	Programs using the line-A are compact (total module only a few hundred
   bytes, compared with the several kilobytes of the GEM libraries.), fast (cos
   parameters are passed directly to the assembler graphics routines at the core
   of GEM), simple (because there is none of GEM's set-up and storage overhead).
	A couple of examples using the Line-A libraries are on this disk.
   See BWDEMO.C and SPTEST.C. Note that these programs will need to be linked
   to the GLIB.BIN module to run properly. Also on this disk is the assembler
   source for the Line-A libraries. Functions in this module are:-

   LONG	a_init()	this function sets up the line-A and returns a pointer
			to the base of the line-A variables (see GLIB.ASM).

   int	a_point(x,y)	returns an integer value representing the color index
			of the pixel at x,y. Note that color indices used by
			GEM are not real color indices (as used by line-A) as
			GEM re-maps the color index for some obscure reason.

   VOID	a_plot(x,y,c)	plot a pixel of color c at point x,y on screen.

   VOID	a_line(x1,y1,x2,y2)
			draw line from point 1 to point 2.

   VOID	a_rectf(x1,y1,x2,y2)
			draw filled rectangle. using current line-A
			pattern pointed to by patptr variable.

   VOID	a_color(c)	set color for line drawing and fill operations.
			(see above note about GEM color indices).

   The following functions will not work witht he first release of TOS
   i.e. version 0.13 which had a bug in the line-A handler code.

   VOID	a_sprite(x,y,sprdef,sprsav)
			draw sprite pointed to by sprdef at x,y. saving
			background at memory pointed to by sprsav.
			You will need some line-A documentation for details
			of sprite definition format although you may find
			enough info in the SPRITE.ASM file.

   VOID	a_unspr(sprsav) undraw the sprite whose background was saved at
			memory pointed to by sprsav.

6) USING THE COMPILER WITH A SINGLE DISK DRIVE is possible although it involves
   quite a lot of disk swapping. You can save yourself a lot of time and
   frustration if you have TOS in ROM (or extra memory) so that there is
   enough free memory to use a RAM disk. Suitable ram-disk software is
   available from several sources (including some public domain). I can
   personally recommend K-ram from Kuma computers (marketed by Antic as
   'A-ram' in the States). A 520ST with TOS in ROM can spare about 200k
   for use as a RAM-disk and still leaves plenty of room for the compiler.

7) NOTE: The Metacomco Lattice-C GEM libraries do not need the static GEM
   array declarations present at the begining of many GEM programs. Since
   these arrays are always used with GEM applications they have been integrated
   into the GEM libraries themselves - see the source file LIB0.ASM on the
   compiler disk. Keeping these array declarations in your program should not
   harm your program although they will not actually be used by the libraries.

LINK68 etc.
-----------
	Please note that LINK68 is a linker provided by Atari as part of the
official Atari ST developers' package. Metacomco products support the format
used by this linker only for sake of compatability. Metacomco are not able
to supply LINK68 or any of the programs in the Atari software developers'
kit. The linker provided with Metacomco products (GST LINK) is functionally
equivalent to Digital Research's LINK68 in all necessary respects.

USING THE GST LINKER
--------------------
	Note that to if all you want to do is turn the output of the assembler
( a .BIN file ) into an executable file, you need only run the linker and give
it the filename (no extension necessary).

e.g. run LINK.TTP with the command line SPRITE

this will produce a file SPRITE.PRG from a file called SPRITE.BIN

If however you want to link together separate object modules e.g. the output
from a compiler and/or separate assembler modules then you will need to provide 
the linker with an appropriate linker control file (see linker documentation).

TOS FILE EXTENSIONS
-------------------
	Most ST executable files have a three letter file extension on the end
of the filename (either .PRG or .TOS or .TTP). This file extension indicates
what type of application the program is. The linker output file defaults to
.PRG filetype but you can rename the file to either of the other extensions
if you wish. GEM desktop starts up the programs differently depending on this
filename extension.

xxxx.PRG files - a GEM application program. TOS will assume that .PRG programs
	 run using GEM and will start them up with a clear desktop headed by
	 the filename of the application. The mouse is left active (and thus
	 appears on the screen as a bee). The console (a primitive i/o device)
	 remains active & useable although the cursor is turned off.

xxxx.TOS files - These are generally programs which do not make use of GEM
	 facilities, usually using console for user i/o. The screen is cleared
	 to background colour (usually white) and the mouse sprite is hidden.
	 The cursor is enabled in it's default state (usually flashing).

xxxx.TTP files - Tos Takes Parameters. This filetype is treated similarly to
	 a .TOS file except that GEM Desktop first presents the user
	 with a dialogue box and accepts a command line. It then starts-up
	 the program passing it the command line string.
 

